# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rip-routing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] A **distance-vector routing protocol** in data networks determines the best route for data packets based on distance.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector routing protocols measure the distance by the number of routers a packet has to pass; one router counts as one hop.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Some distance-vector protocols also take into account network latency and other factors that influence traffic on a given route.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] To determine the best route across a network, routers using a distance-vector protocol exchange information with one another, usually routing tables plus hop counts for destination networks and possibly other traffic information.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector routing protocols also require that a router inform its neighbours of network topology changes periodically.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector routing protocols use the Bellman–Ford algorithm to calculate the best route.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Another way of calculating the best route across a network is based on link cost, and is implemented through link-state routing protocols.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The term *distance vector* refers to the fact that the protocol manipulates *vectors* (arrays) of distances to other nodes in the network.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The distance vector algorithm was the original ARPANET routing algorithm and was implemented more widely in local area networks with the Routing Information Protocol (RIP).
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector routing protocols use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] In these protocols, each router does not possess information about the full network topology.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] It advertises its distance value (DV) calculated to other routers and receives similar advertisements from other routers unless changes are done in the local network or by neighbours (routers).
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Using these routing advertisements each router populates its routing table.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] In the next advertisement cycle, a router advertises updated information from its routing table.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] This process continues until the routing tables of each router converge to stable values.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Some of these protocols have the disadvantage of slow convergence.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Routers that use distance-vector protocol determine the distance between themselves and a destination.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The best route for data through a data network is measured in terms of the numbers of routers (hops) a packet has to pass through to reach its destination network.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Additionally, some distance-vector protocols take into account other traffic information, such as network latency.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] To establish the best route, routers regularly exchange information with neighbouring routers, usually their routing table, hop count for a destination network and possibly other traffic related information.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Routers that implement distance-vector protocol rely purely on the information provided to them by other routers, and do not assess the network topology.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance-vector protocols update the routing tables of routers and determine the route on which a packet will be sent by the *next hop* which is the exit interface of the router and the IP address of the interface of the receiving router.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Distance is a measure of the cost to reach a certain node.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The least cost route between any two nodes is the route with minimum distance.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Updates are performed periodically in a distance-vector protocol where all or part of a router's routing table is sent to all its neighbours that are configured to use the same distance-vector routing protocol.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Once a router has this information it is able to amend its own routing table to reflect the changes and then inform its neighbours of the changes.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] This process has been described as ‘routing by rumour’ because routers are relying on the information they receive from other routers and cannot determine if the information is actually valid and true.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] There are a number of features which can be used to help with instability and inaccurate routing information.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The oldest routing protocol, and the oldest distance-vector protocol, is version 1 of the Routing Information Protocol (RIPv1).
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] RIPv1 was formally standardised in 1988.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] It establishes the shortest path across a network purely on the basis of the hops, that is numbers of routers that need to be passed to reach the destination network.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] RIP is an interior gateway protocol, so it can be used in local area networks (LANs) on interior or border routers.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Routers with RIPv1 implementation exchange their routing tables with neighbouring routers by broadcasting a RIPv1 packet every 30 second into all connected networks.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] RIPv1 is not suitable for large networks as it limits the number of hops to 15.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] This hop limit was introduced to avoid routing loops, but also means that networks that are connected through more than 15 routers are unreachable.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The distance-vector protocol designed for use in wide area networks (WANs) is the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] BGP is an exterior gateway protocol and therefore implemented on border and exterior routers on the Internet.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] It exchanges information between routers through a Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) session.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Routers with BGP implementation determine the shortest path across a network based on a range of factors other than hops.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] BGP can also be configured by administrators so that certain routes are preferred or avoided.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] BGP is used by internet service providers (ISPs) and telecommunication companies.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Among the distance-vector protocols that have been described as a hybrid, because it uses routing methods associated with link-state routing protocols, is the proprietary Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] It was developed by Cisco in the 1980s and was designed to offer better convergence and cause less network traffic between routers than the link-state routing protocol Open Shortest Path First (OSPF).
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Another example of a distance-vector routing protocol is Babel.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The Bellman–Ford algorithm does not prevent routing loops from happening and suffers from the **count to infinity problem**.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The core of the count to infinity problem is that if A tells B that it has a path somewhere, there is no way for B to know if the path has B as a part of it.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] To see the problem, imagine a subnet connected like A–B–C–D–E–F, and let the metric between the routers be "number of jumps".
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] In the vector-update-process B notices that the route to A, which was distance 1, is down – B does not receive the vector update from A.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The problem is, B also gets an update from C, and C is still not aware of the fact that A is down – so it tells B that A is only two jumps from C (C to B to A).
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Since B doesn't know that the path from C to A is through itself (B), it updates its table with the new value "B to A = 2 + 1".
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Later on, B forwards the update to C and due to the fact that A is reachable through B (From C's point of view), C decides to update its table to "C to A = 3 + 1".
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] This slowly propagates through the network until it becomes infinity (in which case the algorithm corrects itself, due to the relaxation property of Bellman-Ford).
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] RIP uses the split horizon with poison reverse technique to reduce the chance of forming loops and uses a maximum number of hops to counter the 'count to infinity' problem.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] These measures avoid the formation of routing loops in some, but not all, cases.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] The addition of a *hold time* (refusing route updates for a few minutes after a route retraction) avoids loop formation in virtually all cases, but causes a significant increase in convergence times.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] More recently, a number of loop-free distance vector protocols have been developed — notable examples are EIGRP, DSDV and Babel.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] These avoid loop formation in all cases, but suffer from increased complexity, and their deployment has been slowed down by the success of link state routing protocols such as OSPF.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] We mark the current time (or iteration) in the algorithm with T, and begin (at time 0, or T=0) by creating distance matrices for each router to its immediate neighbours.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] As we build the routing tables below, the shortest path is highlighted in green, and a new shortest path is highlighted in yellow.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Grey columns indicate nodes that are not neighbors of the current node, and are therefore not considered as a valid direction in its table.
[src:rip-routing/distance-vector-routing-protocol] Red indicates invalid entries in the table since they refer to distances from a node to itself, or via itself.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] In wired computer networking a **hop** occurs when a packet is passed from one network segment to the next.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Data packets pass through routers as they travel between source and destination.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] The **hop count** refers to the number of network devices through which data passes from source to destination (depending on routing protocol, this may include the source/destination, that is, the first hop is counted as hop 0 or hop 1).
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Since store and forward and other latencies are incurred through each hop, a large number of hops between source and destination implies lower real-time performance.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] In wired networks, the hop count refers to the number of networks or network devices through which data passes between source and destination (depending on routing protocol, this may include the source/destination, that is, the first hop is counted as hop 0 or hop 1).
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Thus, hop count is a rough measure of distance between two hosts.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] For a routing protocol using 1-origin hop counts (such as RIP), a hop count of *n* means that *n* networks separate the source host from the destination host.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Other protocols such as DHCP use the term "hop" to refer to the number of times a message has been forwarded.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] On a layer 3 network such as Internet Protocol (IP), each router along the data path constitutes a hop.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] By itself, this metric is, however, not useful for determining the optimum network path, as it does not take into consideration the speed, load, reliability, or latency of any particular hop, but merely the total count.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Nevertheless, some routing protocols, such as Routing Information Protocol (RIP), use hop count as their sole metric.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Each time a router receives a packet, it modifies the packet, decrementing the time to live (TTL).
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] The router discards any packets received with a zero TTL value.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] This prevents packets from endlessly bouncing around the network in the event of routing errors.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Routers are capable of managing hop counts, but other types of network devices (e.g.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Known as *time to live* (TTL) in IPv4, and *hop limit* in IPv6, this field specifies a limit on the number of hops a packet is allowed before being discarded.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Routers modify IP packets as they are forwarded, decrementing the respective TTL or hop limit fields.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Routers do not forward packets with a resultant field of 0 or less.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] This prevents packets from following a loop forever.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] When configuring network devices the *hop* may refer to *next hop*.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] When a hop forwards network traffic the next hop is what the local hop considers to be the next element towards the final destination.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] A routing table usually consists of a list of possible destination networks or IP addresses for which the next hop is known.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] By only storing next-hop information, *next-hop routing* or *next-hop forwarding* reduces the size of routing tables.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] A given gateway only knows one step along the path, not the complete path to a destination.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] If no next hop is known a hop may silently discard a packet or return an error depending on the type of network.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Devices in consumer networks are often only provided with routes for the local network as well as a default gateway as the traffic can only ever reach the local network or be forwarded to the internet service provider.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Routers require multiple routes to be able to forward traffic between different networks.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] In practice routes are configured either implicitly with address assignment by means of a netmask, by manual assignment using tools such as route, or dynamically using configuration protocols like DHCP or routing protocols.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] In TCP/IP networks using Ethernet as the *link layer* the destination is always an IP address, however the next hop is not technically required to be of the same address family.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] As the packet needs to be forwarded on the link layer the next hop needs only to resolve to a link layer address such as a MAC address.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] On Linux for instance the next hop is required to be either an IP address or an interface.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] The address families of the destination address and the next hop need not match, therefore it is possible to forward IPv4 traffic on an IPv6 network and vice versa.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] If no address is provided the destination is assumed to be present on the local link, otherwise the next hop is used.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Either address is then passed to NDP or ARP for IPv6 and IPv4 respectively to be resolved to the link layer address required to pass the packet along on the network stack.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] In other scenarios link layer resolution may require different methods such as a virtual private network which needs to determine the peer to send the packet to.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] What is common to forwarding is that the next hop needs to be logically connected to the current hop, thereby building an uninterrupted chain between source and destination.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] A logical connection does not necessitate a physical connection as the packet may be passed on to a virtual tunnel.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Source routing describes networks in which data is encoded in the packet that allows a hop (such as the source of the packet) to influence routing decisions on intermediary hops.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] This allows for advanced teletraffic engineering used to improve network delay, decrease network congestion, or meet other requirements.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] The traceroute command can be used to measure the number of router hops from one host to another.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Hop counts are often useful to find faults in a network or to discover if routing is indeed correct.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] In a wireless ad hoc network, commonly, every participating node is also acting as a router.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] This means that the terms "hop" and "hop count" are often the subject of confusion.
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] Often, the sending node is simply counted as the first hop, thus yielding the same number for "hops" for both interpretations of "hop" as "traversed routers" and "jumps from node to node".
[src:rip-routing/hop-networking] For example, RFC 6130 defines a "1-hop neighbor" as any other node that is directly reachable via the wireless interface.
[src:rip-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] An **interior gateway protocol** (**IGP**) or **interior routing protocol** is a type of routing protocol used for exchanging routing table information between gateways (commonly routers) *within* an autonomous system (for example, a system of corporate local area networks).
[src:rip-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] This routing information can then be used to route network-layer protocols like IP.
[src:rip-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] Interior gateway protocols can be divided into two categories: distance-vector routing protocols and link-state routing protocols.
[src:rip-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] Specific examples of IGPs include Open Shortest Path First (OSPF), Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Intermediate System to Intermediate System (IS-IS) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:rip-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] By contrast, exterior gateway protocols are used to exchange routing information *between* autonomous systems and rely on IGPs to resolve routes within an autonomous system.
[src:rip-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] Advanced distance vector routing protocols have both the features of distance vector routing protocols and link-state routing protocols.
[src:rip-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] One example is Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The **Routing Information Protocol** (**RIP**) is one of the oldest distance-vector routing protocols which employs the hop count as a routing metric.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIP prevents routing loops by implementing a limit on the number of hops allowed in a path from source to destination.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The largest number of hops allowed for RIP is 15, which limits the size of networks that RIP can support.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIP implements the split horizon, route poisoning, and holddown mechanisms to prevent incorrect routing information from being propagated.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] In RIPv1 routers broadcast updates with their routing table every 30 seconds.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] In the early deployments, routing tables were small enough that the traffic was not significant.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] As networks grew in size, however, it became evident there could be a massive traffic burst every 30 seconds, even if the routers had been initialized at random times.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] In most networking environments, RIP is not the preferred choice of routing protocol, as its time to converge and scalability are poor compared to EIGRP, OSPF, or IS-IS.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] However, it is easy to configure, because RIP does not require any parameters, unlike other protocols.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIP uses the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as its transport protocol, and is assigned the reserved port number 520.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Based on the Bellman–Ford algorithm and the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm, distance-vector routing protocols started to be implemented from 1969 onwards in data networks such as the ARPANET and CYCLADES.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The predecessor of RIP was the Gateway Information Protocol (GWINFO) which was developed by Xerox in the mid-1970s to route its experimental network.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] As part of the Xerox Network Systems (XNS) protocol suite GWINFO transformed into the XNS Routing Information Protocol.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] This XNS RIP in turn became the basis for early routing protocols, such as Novell's IPX RIP, AppleTalk's Routing Table Maintenance Protocol (RTMP), and the IP RIP.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The 1982 Berkeley Software Distribution of the UNIX operating system implemented RIP in the *routed* daemon.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The 4.2BSD release proved popular and became the basis for subsequent UNIX versions, which implemented RIP in the *routed* or *gated* daemon.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Ultimately, RIP had been extensively deployed before the standard, written by Charles Hedrick, was passed as RIPv1 in 1988.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The routing metric used by RIP counts the number of routers that need to be passed to reach a destination IP network.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The hop count 0 denotes a network that is directly connected to the router.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] 16 hops denote a network that is unreachable, according to the RIP hop limit.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] There are three standardized versions of the Routing Information Protocol: *RIPv1* and *RIPv2* for IPv4, and *RIPng* for IPv6.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The original specification of RIP was published in 1988.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] When starting up, and every 30 seconds thereafter, a router with RIPv1 implementation broadcasts to *255.255.255.255* a request message through every RIPv1 enabled interface.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Neighbouring routers receiving the request message respond with a RIPv1 segment, containing their routing table.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The requesting router updates its own routing table, with the reachable IP network address, hop count and next hop, that is the router interface IP address from which the RIPv1 response was sent.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Therefore, a RIPv1 router will in most cases only have one entry for a reachable network, the one with the lowest hop count.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] If a router receives information from two different neighbouring router that the same network is reachable with the same hop count but via two different routes, the network will be entered into the routing table two times with different next hop routers.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The RIPv1 enabled router will then perform what is known as equal-cost load balancing for IP packets.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIPv1 enabled routers not only request the routing tables of other routers every 30 seconds, they also listen to incoming requests from neighbouring routers and send their own routing table in turn.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIPv1 routing tables are therefore updated every 25 to 35 seconds.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The RIPv1 protocol adds a small random time variable to the update time, to avoid routing tables synchronizing across a LAN.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] It was thought, as a result of random initialization, the routing updates would spread out in time, but this was not true in practice.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Sally Floyd and Van Jacobson showed in 1994 that, without slight randomization of the update timer, the timers synchronized over time.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIPv1 can be configured into silent mode, so that a router requests and processes neighbouring routing tables, and keeps its routing table and hop count for reachable networks up to date, but does not needlessly send its own routing table into the network.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Silent mode is commonly implemented to hosts.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The periodic routing updates do not carry subnet information, lacking support for variable length subnet masks (VLSM).
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] This limitation makes it impossible to have different-sized subnets inside of the same network class.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] In other words, all subnets in a network class must have the same size.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] There is also no support for router authentication, making RIP vulnerable to various attacks.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Due to the deficiencies of the original RIP specification, RIP version 2 (RIPv2) was developed in 1993, published in 1994, and declared Internet Standard 56 in 1998.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] It included the ability to carry subnet information, thus supporting Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR).
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] To maintain backward compatibility, the hop count limit of 15 remained.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIPv2 has facilities to fully interoperate with the earlier specification if all *Must Be Zero* protocol fields in the RIPv1 messages are properly specified.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] In addition, a *compatibility switch* feature allows fine-grained interoperability adjustments.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] In an effort to avoid unnecessary load on hosts that do not participate in routing, RIPv2 *multicasts* the entire routing table to all adjacent routers at the address *224.0.0.9*, as opposed to RIPv1 which uses broadcast.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Unicast addressing is still allowed for special applications.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] (MD5) authentication for RIP was introduced in 1997.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Route tags were also added in RIP version 2.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] This functionality allows a distinction between routes learned from the RIP protocol and routes learned from other protocols.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIPng (RIP next generation) is an extension of RIPv2 for support of IPv6, the next generation Internet Protocol.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIPng sends updates on UDP port 521 using the multicast group *ff02::9*.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] RIP messages use the User Datagram Protocol on port 520 and all RIP messages exchanged between routers are encapsulated in a UDP datagram.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Asking a neighbouring RIPv1 enabled router to send its routing table.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Controls the interval between two gratuitous Response Messages.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The response message is broadcast to all its RIP enabled interface.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The invalid timer specifies how long a routing entry can be in the routing table without being updated.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] This is also called as expiration Timer.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] After the timer expires the hop count of the routing entry will be set to 16, marking the destination as unreachable.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The flush timer controls the time between the route is invalidated or marked as unreachable and removal of entry from the routing table.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] This is 60 seconds longer than Invalid timer.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] So for 60 seconds the router will be advertising about this unreachable route to all its neighbours.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The hold-down timer is started per route entry, when the hop count is changing from lower value to higher value.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] This allows the route to get stabilized.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] During this time no update can be done to that routing entry.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] The default value of this timer is 180 seconds.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Cisco's proprietary Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (IGRP) was a somewhat more capable protocol than RIP.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] It belongs to the same basic family of distance-vector routing protocols.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Cisco has ceased support and distribution of IGRP in their router software.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] It was replaced by the Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP) which is a completely new design.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] While EIGRP still uses a distance-vector model, it relates to IGRP only in using the same composite routing metric.
[src:rip-routing/routing-information-protocol] Both IGRP and EIGRP calculated a single composite metric for each route, from a formula of five variables: bandwidth, delay, reliability, load, and MTU; though on Cisco routers, by default, only bandwidth and delay are used in this calculation.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] A **routing protocol** specifies how routers communicate with each other to distribute information that enables them to select paths between nodes on a computer network.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Routers perform the traffic directing functions on the Internet; data packets are forwarded through the networks of the internet from router to router until they reach their destination computer.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Routing algorithms determine the specific choice of route.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Each router has a prior knowledge only of networks attached to it directly.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] A routing protocol shares this information first among immediate neighbors, and then throughout the network.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] This way, routers gain knowledge of the topology of the network.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] The ability of routing protocols to dynamically adjust to changing conditions such as disabled connections and components and route data around obstructions is what gives the Internet its fault tolerance and high availability.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Certain additional characteristics such as multilayer interfacing may also be employed as a means of distributing uncompromised networking gateways to authorized ports.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] This has the added benefit of preventing issues with routing protocol loops.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Many routing protocols are defined in technical standards documents called RFCs.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Interior gateway protocols (IGPs) exchange routing information within a single routing domain.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Exterior gateway protocols exchange routing information between autonomous systems.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Many software implementations exist for most of the common routing protocols.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Examples of open-source applications are Bird Internet routing daemon, Quagga, GNU Zebra, OpenBGPD, OpenOSPFD, and XORP.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Some network certification courses distinguish between routing protocols and *routed* protocols.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] A **routed protocol** is used to deliver application traffic.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] It provides appropriate addressing information in its internet layer or network layer to allow a packet to be forwarded from one network to another.
[src:rip-routing/routing-protocol] Examples of routed protocols are the Internet Protocol (IP) and Internetwork Packet Exchange (IPX).
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] In computer networking, **split-horizon route advertisement** is a method of preventing routing loops in distance-vector routing protocols by prohibiting a router from advertising a route back onto the interface from which it was learned.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The concept was suggested in 1974 by Torsten Cegrell, and originally implemented in the ARPANET-inspired Swedish network TIDAS.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] Whereas under split horizon N does not send any information through I, under poison reverse node N tells a white-lie.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] In this example, network node *A* routes packets to node *B* in order to reach node *C*.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The links between the nodes are distinct point-to-point links.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] According to the split-horizon rule, node *A* does not advertise its route for *C* (namely *A* to *B* to *C*) back to *B*.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] On the surface, this seems redundant since *B* will never route via node *A* because the route costs more than the direct route from *B* to *C*.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] However, if the link between *B* and *C* goes down, and *B* had received a route from *A* to *C*, *B* could end up using that route via *A*.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] *A* would send the packet right back to *B*, creating a loop.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] With the split-horizon rule in place, this particular loop scenario cannot happen, improving convergence time in complex, highly-redundant environments.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] Split-horizon routing with **poison reverse** is a variant of split-horizon route advertising in which a router actively advertises routes as unreachable over the interface over which they were learned by setting the route metric to infinite (16 for RIP).
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The effect of such an announcement is to immediately remove most looping routes before they can propagate through the network.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The main disadvantage of poison reverse is that it can significantly increase the size of routing announcements in certain fairly common network topologies, but it allows for the improvement of the overall efficiency of the network in case of faults.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] Split horizon states that if a neighboring router sends a route to a router, the receiving router will not propagate this route back to the advertising router on the same interface.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] With route poisoning, when a router detects that one of its connected routes has failed, the router will poison the route by assigning an infinite metric to it and advertising it to neighbors.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] When a router advertises a poisoned route to its neighbors, its neighbors break the rule of split horizon and send back to the originator the same poisoned route, called a poison reverse.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] In order to give the router enough time to propagate the poisoned route and to ensure that no routing loops occur while propagation occurs, the routers implement a hold-down mechanism.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The basic idea of poison reverse is to make sure that a path does not turn back into the same node if a cost has changed within the network.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] An example of this would be: Node Z routes via node Y to destination X.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] If the cost between Y and X increases, the count to infinity problem will occur.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] To avoid it, we implement poison reverse.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] As long as Z routes via node Y to get to X, Z will tell a white lie to Y: Z will announce to Y an infinite cost to the destination X.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The numbers on the edges are the costs of the links.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The first, second and third lines correspond to node Z, node Y and node X distance vectors, respectively.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The following matrix contains the estimates of the distances from Z to all the other nodes in the network through each of its neighbors.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] As Z routes via Y to get to X, the cost-to-go from Z to X is 3.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The poison reverse kicks in when a node broadcasts its distance vector to its neighbors.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] As we see in the distance vector that is broadcast to node Y the end destination X has an infinity value.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] Poison reverse solves the count-to-infinity problem since if the link between Y and X has its cost increased to, say, 70, then Y and Z will not bounce between each other and instead directly try another path.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] Alternatively, if poison reverse is not used, when the link between Y and X has its cost increased, Y will announce the news to Z.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] However, before announcing, Y may leverage the fact that Z can reach X with a cost of 3 to decide that Y can reach X with a cost of 4.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] Then, Z updates its cost-to-go to X, through Y, as 5.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] Following that, Y updates its cost-to-go to X, through Z, as 6, and so on, until cost-to-go from Z to X reaches 30.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] At this point, after 30 iterations, the algorithm converges.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] If the link between C and D would fail node C can still try to go through B to get to the destination.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] B was already routing through A, and will continue doing so.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] Now, A cannot route through B, due to poison reverse, but at this point A will eventually receive a message from C announcing that C has a route with cost 6 to D, where c(C,B)+distance(B,D)=3+(1+1+1)=3+3=6.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] In summary, after failure of CD, C will update, followed by A, B, C, A, B, C and so on.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] From there we have a loop that we can not solve with poison reverse.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] This can though be completed with an implementation of a distance vector protocol called RIP.
[src:rip-routing/split-horizon-route-advertisement] The split-horizon method is effective and simple to implement, and is therefore used by most distance-vector protocols.
